E. COLI & GROUND BEEF, QUANTITATIVE RISK ASSESSMENT (02)
********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
See Also
E. coli & ground beef, quantitative risk assessment 980516083125
Date: Wed, 20 May 1998 11:47:00 +0700 (T)
From: Goldwater, Paul <goldwaterp@mail.wch.sa.gov.au>

The abstract from the paper by Michael H. Cassin, Anna M. Lammerding, Ewen
C.D. Todd, William Ross, R.Stephen McColl raises some important issues with
respect to our understanding of enterohaemorrhagic E. coli (EHEC).
Although I haven't read the paper itself, it is plain to see from the
abstract that the authors are not aware of the very low infective dose
(often <10 cfu's) of EHEC.
The authors' hypothetical mitigation strategy proposed that refrigeration
would reduce the average risk of illness by 80%, yet it is hard to
reconcile this in the light of an apparent absence of a relationship of
risk with infective dose. (In investigations of outbreaks, the numbers of
organisms in the incriminated foods has been consistently extremely low).
Absence of refrigeration has not played a significant role in reported
outbreaks. It should also be noted that refrigeration could be
counterproductive in some situations such as with fermented sausage; the
infective dose would be preserved and the pH and water content would be
maintained for optimum EHEC survival.
In addition, the focus on EHEC O157:H7 perpetuated by Cassin et al. shows a
failure to recognise the important role of non-O157:H7 EHEC in human
disease. My colleague Karl Bettelheim and I have demonstrated multiple
EHEC infections occurred in most cases of HUS during the Adelaide epidemic,
and a trend for complications (Chronic renal failure, infarcts, etc.) was
shown [mean of 12.5 strains compared with 7.8 strains for uncomplicated
disease.
Multiple strain infection is not surprising given the fact that multiple
STEC are present in the animals from which the contaminated meat comes. It
would seem improbable that O157:H7 would rise above its cousins and form a
"pure" contaminating population ready to strike the susceptible host as a
single infecting agent! In the same way we commonly observe several
strains of Salmonella from a single source simultaneously infecting
patients.
We review the whole issue of how outbreaks have been microbiologically
investigated and demonstrate that in the vast majority of outbreaks only
O157:H7 has been sought. The role of non-O157 EHEC is placed into proper
perspective. The review is soon to be published in J Med Microbiol.
--
Paul N. Goldwater
Senior Consultant Clinical Microbiologist,
Microbiology & Infectious Diseases Department
The Women's & Children's Hospital
North Adelaide
South Australia 5006
