[I haven't read the paper myself yet, so I will limit my comments to noting
that this kind of comment is what makes risk assessment an attractive tool.
One of the least understood but most important benefits of a comprehensive
risk assessment is to focus our attention on areas of importance which have
yet to be addressed. I don't know if the paper's author's address this
issue until I read it or at least talk to them. It is important to
remember that risk assessment is an iterative process so that if Dr.
Goldwater's data hasn't been included in the initial quantitative risk
assessment, it can be easily included in the next iteration. At this point,
I suggest three things: first, we all read the paper, next, I see if the
authors can shed some light on how and why they handled infective dose and
multiple strain infection issues in the way they did and finally we
congratulate Cassin et al. for moving the E. coli O157:H7 risk assessment
dialogue along. - Mod.PC
......................................pc/es
